ional wedding rites. In Framing the Bride, we see how this practice is also a creative response to U.S. domination of transnational visual imagery—how bridal photographers and their subjects take the project of globalization into their own hands, defining its terms for their lives even as they expose the emptiness of its images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBridal shopsxTaiwan. 0aBridal shopszTaiwan. 0aWedding photographyxTaiwanxTaiwan. 0aWedding photographyzTaiwan. 0aWedding supplies and services industryxTaiwan. 0aWedding supplies and services industryzTaiwan. 0aWeddingsxEquipment and suppliesxTaiwan. 0aWeddingszTaiwanxEquipment and supplies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aartifacts.  abeauty standards.  abridal hair.  abridal makeup.  abridal photography.  abridal.  abride to be.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  amakeover.  amakeup artist.  amarriage.  amatrimony.  amtv.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  ataiwan.  ataiwanese.  atransformation.  avictorian england.  awedding day.  awedding photography.  awedding photos.  awedding prep.  awedding.  awestern beauty standards.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093003240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930032/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles